00:09:24.768 --> 00:09:27.375
and only intervene on the
students that are stuck.

00:09:27.375 --> 00:09:29.493
So you could do a very
focused intervention

00:09:29.493 --> 00:09:31.407
and be armed with the right data to do it.

00:09:31.407 --> 00:09:34.035
Or even better get a student
who's already proficient in that

00:09:34.035 --> 00:09:35.774
to intervene on that student

00:09:35.774 --> 00:09:38.543
and then you get all the benefits
of learning something even deeper

00:09:38.543 --> 00:09:40.827
when you yourself are the teacher.

00:09:40.827 --> 00:09:43.326
They decided to do it.

00:09:43.326 --> 00:09:49.031
In Los Altos we have two fifth grade
classes and two seventh grade classes

00:09:49.031 --> 00:09:51.971
and they're using this
as their core curriculum.

00:09:51.971 --> 00:09:54.946
What I want to emphasize here
and it's not always made clear

00:09:54.946 --> 00:09:57.939
is when I talk about this to
people, a lot of people will say,

00:09:57.939 --> 00:09:59.038
"Oh this awesome."

00:09:59.038 --> 00:10:02.458
Self-pace learning, mastery based,
differentiate in instruction

00:10:02.458 --> 00:10:05.275
but there is a crowd that starts
to get a little suspicious.

00:10:05.275 --> 00:10:10.326
They start saying well, "This sounds
like you're automating things"

00:10:10.326 --> 00:10:12.693
"but it sounds like it's very robotic."

00:10:12.693 --> 00:10:18.323
"It sounds like kids in front of a
computer just doing exercises all day,"

00:10:18.323 --> 00:10:20.882
"listening to videos, not
interacting with each other."

00:10:20.882 --> 00:10:23.236
"It sounds like you're
marginalizing the teacher."

00:10:23.236 --> 00:10:25.308
"It sounds your deskilling the teacher,"

00:10:25.308 --> 00:10:29.859
"that you're making them just
do what the computers can't."

00:10:29.859 --> 00:10:33.193
What I want to emphasize
here is the exact opposite.

00:10:33.193 --> 00:10:35.466
What we're seeing in those
classrooms in Los Altos,

00:10:35.466 --> 00:10:38.879
is we're seeing every
moment of that teachers time

00:10:38.879 --> 00:10:42.776
is spent interacting with
her students, being a mentor.

00:10:42.776 --> 00:10:45.984
These students are getting one on one
with the teacher multiple times a week.

00:10:45.984 --> 00:10:49.228
When I was in school I was lucky
to get that even a few times,

00:10:49.228 --> 00:10:50.860
and even in your whole career.

00:10:50.860 --> 00:10:52.307
Multiple times a week.

00:10:52.307 --> 00:10:56.655
They aren't doing this at the
expense of project based learning

00:10:56.655 --> 00:10:57.592
or investigations.

00:10:57.592 --> 00:11:00.430
What this is allowing the teacher
to do, it liberates the classroom.

00:11:00.430 --> 00:11:03.184
So now that they can do more
of the project based learning,

00:11:03.184 --> 00:11:04.707
they can do more of the investigations.

00:11:04.707 --> 00:11:08.785
These classrooms in Los Altos, there
is more of that creative activity,

00:11:08.785 --> 00:11:13.009
more of this interaction, more of
this experimenting with the world

00:11:13.009 --> 00:11:15.016
than you would see in any other classroom.

00:11:15.016 --> 00:11:16.633
So for the first time because
we have this technology

00:11:16.633 --> 00:11:18.184
it's not an either or proposition.

00:11:18.184 --> 00:11:20.724
You have this kind of camps
of mathematical instruction.

00:11:20.724 --> 00:11:22.989
Do you do kind of the traditional,

00:11:22.989 --> 00:11:27.011
do a lot of problems, lecture and
see a lot of traditional problems?

00:11:27.011 --> 00:11:29.744
Or do you do the project based
learning where you investigate things?

00:11:29.744 --> 00:11:32.099
Our answer is now we can do both.

00:11:32.099 --> 00:11:34.784
Even better, even on the instruction
itself there's these debates

00:11:34.784 --> 00:11:37.559
between old Math and
new Math, how you to it?

00:11:37.559 --> 00:11:40.243
The value when you have on
demand video, you can do both.

00:11:40.243 --> 00:11:43.265
You can actually expose the
students to every possible way

00:11:43.265 --> 00:11:44.882
that there is to learn Mathematics.

00:11:44.882 --> 00:11:48.696
In the same classroom, you have
one kid doing third grade Math

00:11:48.696 --> 00:11:51.228
and you have one kid doing
Algebra, and that's great.

00:11:51.228 --> 00:11:55.183
The student doing the third grade Math
needs to be doing the third grade Math.

00:11:55.183 --> 00:11:57.180
Here she needs to fill out those gaps,

00:11:57.180 --> 00:12:00.763
and the student who's doing the
Algebra should be able to run forward

00:12:00.763 --> 00:12:02.236
and do the Algebra.

