00:13:28.061 --> 00:13:29.895
and I'll just read a couple real quick.

00:13:29.895 --> 00:13:32.844
There's one, "My eldest kid is
dancing around in my room here"

00:13:32.844 --> 00:13:34.783
"because she is so excited
that she finally found someone"

00:13:34.783 --> 00:13:36.401
"that teaches like this."

00:13:36.401 --> 00:13:41.021
I feel uncomfortable, I don't like doing
the self praise, I mean I don't ...

00:13:41.021 --> 00:13:47.160
But what's cool here is that
this girl she wasn't just happy.

00:13:47.160 --> 00:13:48.778
When she learned something,

00:13:48.778 --> 00:13:50.640
when she was actually able
to connect with the material

00:13:50.640 --> 00:13:52.356
it wasn't like "Oh I'm
going to nail the exam."

00:13:52.356 --> 00:13:55.597
She felt the visceral desire to dance.

00:13:55.597 --> 00:13:58.303
(audience laughing)

00:13:58.303 --> 00:14:05.973
(applauding)

00:14:05.973 --> 00:14:07.971
There's all sorts of ... this is a letter

00:14:07.971 --> 00:14:11.504
and this takes me back to my college
days when I didn't have a girlfriend.

00:14:11.504 --> 00:14:15.119
I don't know if these boys at
Bellarmine can relate to this comment.

00:14:15.119 --> 00:14:16.969
(audience laughing)

00:14:16.969 --> 00:14:19.097
This is a comment from a college student,

00:14:19.097 --> 00:14:21.886
"There's always so much else that
a student has on their mind."

00:14:21.886 --> 00:14:23.799
"What is a pretty girl
looking like today?"

00:14:23.799 --> 00:14:26.079
"What was the professor like
when they were a student?"

00:14:26.079 --> 00:14:28.121
"Should I talk to the
pretty girl after class?"

00:14:28.121 --> 00:14:31.251
"Will I include last weekends
event in a book about my life?"

00:14:31.251 --> 00:14:33.361
"That the slightest drifting of focus"

00:14:33.361 --> 00:14:36.497
"quickly turns into a fruitless two
hours spent daydreaming or unconscious."

00:14:36.497 --> 00:14:38.983
"Please continue what you are doing."

00:14:38.983 --> 00:14:41.309
(audience laughing)

00:14:41.309 --> 00:14:45.099
(applauding)

00:14:45.099 --> 00:14:47.974
It was actually a much longer
letter that I had to reduct,

00:14:47.974 --> 00:14:50.466
it wasn't appropriate for this audience.

00:14:50.466 --> 00:14:52.269
(audience laughing)

00:14:52.269 --> 00:14:56.519
This is what I got two days ago,
"I've taken Calculus 1 three times."

00:14:56.519 --> 00:14:58.072
"The first time I didn't pass the class,"

00:14:58.072 --> 00:14:59.630
"the second time I had to drop the class."

00:14:59.630 --> 00:15:02.268
"My girlfriend's mom
told me about the site,"

00:15:02.268 --> 00:15:04.211
"she heard about it in a
conference, I checked it out."

00:15:04.211 --> 00:15:07.013
"I began supplementing, proceeding and
sometimes even replacing my lectures"

00:15:07.013 --> 00:15:10.507
"with your videos and I received
an 84% on my first midterm."

00:15:10.507 --> 00:15:12.250
This is the third time he's taking it.

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:14.590
"I almost cried, I was so happy."

00:15:14.590 --> 00:15:18.667
When I first try, it's 84 that's
a good score, why's he crying?

00:15:18.667 --> 00:15:22.779
"Especially because the
class average was a 47%."

00:15:22.779 --> 00:15:30.370
(applauding)

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:31.796
"Now the second midterm is coming up,"

00:15:31.796 --> 00:15:34.551
"I feel confident enough to say that I
will most likely get an A in the class."

00:15:34.551 --> 00:15:36.631
"Since my major depends
on me passing the class,"

00:15:36.631 --> 00:15:39.165
"I want to thank you for helping
me save my college career."

00:15:40.334 --> 00:15:44.553
It's pretty a mind blowing stuff

00:15:44.553 --> 00:15:48.598
and I think you can imagine why I quit
my day job as a hedge fund manager.

00:15:48.598 --> 00:15:51.258
Wasn't quite as much psychic reward.

00:15:51.258 --> 00:15:57.322
(applauding)

00:15:57.322 --> 00:15:59.639
I think the take away here is that ...

00:15:59.639 --> 00:16:02.885
and this is the learning that we never
want to forget as an organization

00:16:02.885 --> 00:16:07.821
is that, people come to the Khan
Academy wanting to just fill in the gap.

00:16:07.821 --> 00:16:09.552
They have an exam, they
want to pass an exam,

00:16:09.552 --> 00:16:12.210
but once they actually experience
what it's like to learn,

00:16:12.210 --> 00:16:13.603
it doesn't matter who they are.

00:16:13.603 --> 00:16:15.343
It could be the student
who's about to drop out.

00:16:15.343 --> 00:16:17.807
Once they actually experience
it for the first time in life

00:16:17.807 --> 00:16:19.144
they get addicted.

00:16:19.144 --> 00:16:24.230
It's a natural high, it's something that
we innately, all humans want to have.

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:26.305
That's something as an organization,
we don't want to ever forget.

00:16:26.305 --> 00:16:28.845
That if we can form these
human bonds using technology,

00:16:28.845 --> 00:16:31.249
that's what's actually going
to allow us to succeed.

00:16:31.249 --> 00:16:35.026
I want to leave you with
one quick little story

00:16:35.026 --> 00:16:39.393
from one of the Los Altos classrooms last
week that kind of hits the point home.

00:16:39.393 --> 00:16:42.091
There was a reporter
from NBC doing a story

00:16:42.091 --> 00:16:44.595
on what we're doing in that classroom.

00:16:44.595 --> 00:16:48.546
And there's a little fifth grader
and she's doing trigonometry

00:16:48.546 --> 00:16:50.973
and actually all of the
boys are very envious of her

00:16:50.973 --> 00:16:53.345
because she has the most badges and
points and all of that other things.

00:16:53.345 --> 00:16:56.228
The reporter sits down
next to her and says,

00:16:56.228 --> 00:16:58.724
"Do you think this is fifth grade Math?"

00:16:58.724 --> 00:17:01.880
Then the little girl has a mischievous
smile and she looks at the reporter

00:17:01.880 --> 00:17:04.575
and she goes, "No, I
think it's sixth grade."

00:17:04.575 --> 00:17:06.596
(audience laughing)

00:17:06.596 --> 00:17:07.462
Thank you.

00:17:07.462 --> 00:17:15.210
(applauding)

